The two-step dividend growth approach refers to the growth of a dividend that occurs in two stages where the first stage is usually a stage of unstable growth and the second stage is when a constant growth rate is applied to the dividend. 

It is also important that we recall that the present value of a company's stock price can be represented as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Present value of company's stock}&=\text{Sum of present value of future dividend payments}+\text{Present value of stock price at current time}
\end{aligned}$$

We can then represent the present value of all growth rates as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{D}_0(1+\text{g}_1)\times\dfrac{1-\left(\frac{1+\text{g}_1}{1+\text{R}}\right)^t}{\text{R}-\text{g}_1}
&\end{aligned}$$

Where,

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{D}_0&=\text{Current dividend}\\
\text{g}_1&=\text{Growth rate of dividend at the first step}\\
\text{t}&=\text{Time}\\
\text{R}&=\text{Required rate of return}
\end{aligned}$$

The equation above represents the present value of all dividends until time $t$ which is also the same as the left side of the expression presented in the book. 

Moreover, we can then use the constant dividend model to represent the present value of the stock price at current time $t$. This will give us:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_t
&=\dfrac{\text{D}_{t+1}}{\text{R}-\text{g}_2}
\end{aligned}$$

Where,

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_t&=\text{Present value of the company's stock at time t}\\
\text{D}_t&=\text{Dividend at time t}\\
\text{R}&=\text{Required rate of return}\\
\text{g}_2&=\text{Growth rate at the second stage}
\end{aligned}$$

We can then substitute the formula in Step 5 to the formula in Step 4:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{P}_t
&=\dfrac{\text{D}_0(1+\text{g}_1)^t(1+\text{g}_2)}{\text{R}-\text{g}_2}
\end{aligned}$$

In order to get the present value, we will simply multiply it by one plus the growth rate raised to $t$:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Present value of company's stock price at time t}&=\dfrac{\text{D}_0(1+\text{g}_1)^t(1+\text{g}_2)}{\text{R}-\text{g}_2}\times\dfrac{1}{(1+\text{R})^t}

\end{aligned}$$

This expression represents the present value of the company's stock at time $t$ which is the right side of the expression in Step 2.
